{
  "texts": [
    "Plasmids are potentially mobile genetic elements that facilitate transfer of DNA between bacteria.",
    "Plasmid-mediated antibiotic resistance is a growing problem worldwide and is especially associated with Enterobacterales [78,79].",
    "We find, however, that most antibiotic resistance genes in the gut microbiota are predicted to be chromosomally encoded, though we cannot exclude the possibility that these ARGs are located on mobile genetic elements.",
    "To assess the mobility of resistance genes, techniques are needed that can link ARGs to their host organism, such as Meta-HiC [62] or OIL-PCR [80].",
    "ConclusionsOur study points towards possibilities and limitations of the use of FMT for the eradication of MDR bacteria in the gut."
  ]
}